<div id="sendoutlook">
  <% if @partial_is_popup %>
  <a href="#" onclick="close_csv()">x Close Window</a>
  <% end %>

  <center>
    <p><b>To upload an Outlook style CSV file of contacts</b></p>
    <br />
    <p>To export a CSV or tab-delimited text file from Outlook:</p>
    <br />

    <p>  1. Open Outlook</p>
    <p>  2. Select "Import and Export" from the File menu</p>
    <p>  3. When the wizard opens, select "Export to a file" and click "Next" </p>
    <p>  4. Select "Comma separated values (Windows)" and click "Next"</p>
    <p>  5. Select the Contacts folder you would like to export and click "Next" </p>
    <p>  6. Choose a filename and a place to save the file (for instance, "Contacts.csv" on the Desktop), then click "Next"</p>
    <p>  7. Confirm what you are exporting: make sure the checkbox next to "Export..." is checked and click "Finish"</p>
    <br />
    <p>To upload your file to TheWeddingRegistry, simply hit "Browse" below and select the contact file you've just created.</p>
    <br />
    <p>Outlook style CSV files can be exported from other mail providers and used on TheWeddingRegistry as well!</p>
    <p>Some of these are: Outlook Express, Windows Address Book, Palm Desktop, GMail, Windows Mail, and LinkedIn</p>
    <br />
    <%= form_tag({:controller => :contact_lists,:action => :import_from_outlook_post}, :multipart => true) do %>
    <div id="csv_import" style="display: inline;">
      <p>Outlook CSV file: <input name="csv" type="file"></p>
      <br />
      <%= submit_tag "Browse",class: "btn btn-success" %>
    </div>
    <% end %>
  </center>
</div>
